<doc id="381013" wikidata="Q1136376" url="?curid=381013" title="Support (mathematics)">
<text>In mathematics, the support of a real-valued function formula_1 is the subset of the function domain of elements that are not mapped to zero. If the domain of formula_1 is a topological space, then the support of formula_1 is instead defined as the smallest closed set containing all points not mapped to zero. This concept is used widely in mathematical analysis.

==Formulation==

Suppose that formula_4 is a real-valued function whose domain is an arbitrary set formula_5 The of formula_6 written formula_7 is the set of points in formula_8 where formula_1 is non-zero:
formula_10

The support of formula_1 is the smallest subset of formula_8 with the property that formula_1 is zero on the subset&#x27;s complement. If formula_14 for all but a finite number of points formula_15 then formula_1 is said to have .

If the set formula_8 has an additional structure (for example, a topology), then the support of formula_1 is defined in an analogous way as the smallest subset of formula_8 of an appropriate type such that formula_1 vanishes in an appropriate sense on its complement. The notion of support also extends in a natural way to functions taking values in more general sets than formula_21 and to other objects, such as measures or distributions.

==Closed support==

The most common situation occurs when formula_8 is a topological space (such as the real line or formula_23-dimensional Euclidean space) and formula_4 is a continuous real- (or complex-) valued function. In this case, the of formula_1, formula_26, or the of formula_1, is defined topologically as the closure (taken in formula_8) of the subset of formula_8 where formula_1 is non-zero that is,
formula_31Since the intersection of closed sets is closed, formula_26 is the intersection of all closed sets that contain the set-theoretic support of formula_33 Note that if the function formula_34 is defined on an open subset formula_35, then the closure is still taken with respect to formula_8 and not with respect to the ambient formula_37.

For example, if formula_38 is the function defined by
formula_39
then formula_26, the support of formula_1, or the closed support of formula_1, is the closed interval formula_43 since formula_1 is non-zero on the open interval formula_45 and the closure of this set is formula_46

The notion of closed support is usually applied to continuous functions, but the definition makes sense for arbitrary real or complex-valued functions on a topological space, and some authors do not require that formula_4 (or formula_48) be continuous.

==Compact support==

Functions with &#x27; on a topological space formula_8 are those whose closed support is a compact subset of formula_5 If formula_8 is the real line, or formula_23-dimensional Euclidean space, then a function has compact support if and only if it has &#x27;, since a subset of formula_53 is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.

For example, the function formula_38 defined above is a continuous function with compact support formula_46 If formula_56 is a smooth function then because formula_1 is identically formula_58 on the open subset formula_59 all of formula_1&#x27;s partial derivatives of all orders are also identically formula_58 on formula_62 

The condition of compact support is stronger than the condition of vanishing at infinity. For example, the function formula_38 defined by
formula_64
vanishes at infinity, since formula_65 as formula_66 but its support formula_21 is not compact.

Real-valued compactly supported smooth functions on a Euclidean space are called bump functions. Mollifiers are an important special case of bump functions as they can be used in distribution theory to create sequences of smooth functions approximating nonsmooth (generalized) functions, via convolution.

In good cases, functions with compact support are dense in the space of functions that vanish at infinity, but this property requires some technical work to justify in a given example. As an intuition for more complex examples, and in the language of limits, for any formula_68 any function formula_1 on the real line formula_21 that vanishes at infinity can be approximated by choosing an appropriate compact subset formula_71 of formula_21 such that
formula_73
for all formula_15 where formula_75 is the indicator function of formula_76 Every continuous function on a compact topological space has compact support since every closed subset of a compact space is indeed compact.

==Essential support==

If formula_8 is a topological measure space with a Borel measure formula_78 (such as formula_79 or a Lebesgue measurable subset of formula_79 equipped with Lebesgue measure), then one typically identifies functions that are equal formula_78-almost everywhere. In that case, the of a measurable function formula_4 written formula_83 is defined to be the smallest closed subset formula_84 of formula_8 such that formula_86 formula_78-almost everywhere outside formula_88 Equivalently, formula_89 is the complement of the largest open set on which formula_86 formula_78-almost everywhere
formula_92

The essential support of a function formula_1 depends on the measure formula_78 as well as on formula_6 and it may be strictly smaller than the closed support. For example, if formula_96 is the Dirichlet function that is formula_58 on irrational numbers and formula_98 on rational numbers, and formula_99 is equipped with Lebesgue measure, then the support of formula_1 is the entire interval formula_101 but the essential support of formula_1 is empty, since formula_1 is equal almost everywhere to the zero function.

In analysis one nearly always wants to use the essential support of a function, rather than its closed support, when the two sets are different, so formula_89 is often written simply as formula_26 and referred to as the support.

==Generalization==

If formula_106 is an arbitrary set containing zero, the concept of support is immediately generalizable to functions formula_107 Support may also be defined for any algebraic structure with identity (such as a group, monoid, or composition algebra), in which the identity element assumes the role of zero. For instance, the family formula_108 of functions from the natural numbers to the integers is the uncountable set of integer sequences. The subfamily formula_109 is the countable set of all integer sequences that have only finitely many nonzero entries.

Functions of finite support are used in defining algebraic structures such as group rings and free abelian groups.

==In probability and measure theory==
In probability theory, the support of a probability distribution can be loosely thought of as the closure of the set of possible values of a random variable having that distribution. There are, however, some subtleties to consider when dealing with general distributions defined on a sigma algebra, rather than on a topological space.

More formally, if formula_110 is a random variable on formula_111 then the support of formula_8 is the smallest closed set formula_113 such that formula_114

In practice however, the support of a discrete random variable formula_8 is often defined as the set formula_116 and the support of a continuous random variable formula_8 is defined as the set formula_118 where formula_119 is a probability density function of formula_8 (the set-theoretic support). 

Note that the word can refer to the logarithm of the likelihood of a probability density function.

==Support of a distribution==

It is possible also to talk about the support of a distribution, such as the Dirac delta function formula_121 on the real line. In that example, we can consider test functions formula_122 which are smooth functions with support not including the point formula_123 Since formula_124 (the distribution formula_125 applied as linear functional to formula_84) is formula_58 for such functions, we can say that the support of formula_125 is formula_129 only. Since measures (including probability measures) on the real line are special cases of distributions, we can also speak of the support of a measure in the same way.

Suppose that formula_1 is a distribution, and that formula_131 is an open set in Euclidean space such that, for all test functions formula_132 such that the support of formula_132 is contained in formula_134 formula_135 Then formula_1 is said to vanish on formula_137 Now, if formula_1 vanishes on an arbitrary family formula_139 of open sets, then for any test function formula_132 supported in formula_141 a simple argument based on the compactness of the support of formula_132 and a partition of unity shows that formula_143 as well. Hence we can define the of formula_1 as the complement of the largest open set on which formula_1 vanishes. For example, the support of the Dirac delta is formula_146

==Singular support==

In Fourier analysis in particular, it is interesting to study the of a distribution. This has the intuitive interpretation as the set of points at which a distribution .

For example, the Fourier transform of the Heaviside step function can, up to constant factors, be considered to be formula_147 (a function) at formula_148 While formula_149 is clearly a special point, it is more precise to say that the transform of the distribution has singular support formula_129: it cannot accurately be expressed as a function in relation to test functions with support including formula_123 It be expressed as an application of a Cauchy principal value integral.

For distributions in several variables, singular supports allow one to define and understand Huygens&#x27; principle in terms of mathematical analysis. Singular supports may also be used to understand phenomena special to distribution theory, such as attempts to &#x27;multiply&#x27; distributions (squaring the Dirac delta function fails – essentially because the singular supports of the distributions to be multiplied should be disjoint).

==Family of supports==

An abstract notion of on a topological space formula_152 suitable for sheaf theory, was defined by Henri Cartan. In extending Poincaré duality to manifolds that are not compact, the &#x27;compact support&#x27; idea enters naturally on one side of the duality; see for example Alexander–Spanier cohomology.

Bredon, &quot;Sheaf Theory&quot; (2nd edition, 1997) gives these definitions. A family formula_153 of closed subsets of formula_8 is a , if it is down-closed and closed under finite union. Its is the union over formula_155 A family of supports that satisfies further that any formula_156 in formula_153 is, with the subspace topology, a paracompact space; and has some formula_158 in formula_153 which is a neighbourhood. If formula_8 is a locally compact space, assumed Hausdorff, the family of all compact subsets satisfies the further conditions, making it paracompactifying.

